{"title_page": "Vinod Lingala", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Orphan|date=March 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|image = \n| name = Vinod Lingala\n| birth_place = [[Warangal]], [[India]]\n| years_active = 2008-present\n| occupation = [[Film Director]], [[Screenwriter]]\n}}\n'''Vinod Lingala''' is an Indian film director and writer. He did his Masters in Practical Film making from MET Film School, London, UK. He then pursued his M.S. in Global Innovation management in The University of Strathclyde, Glasgow, United Kingdom and University of Alborg, Alborg, Denmark and worked as a Product Design Engineer for Martin Professional A/S, Denmark before he started his film career as an associate director in Indian cinema.  His directorial debut Telugu feature film ''Guppedantha Prema'' was well appreciated by critics and viewers alike.\n\n==Early life==\nVinod Lingala did his schooling in Bishop Beretta High School. He pursued his B.Tech from Kakatiya Institute of Technology and Science and later bagged a huge European Union Scholarship for Masters in Global Innovation management in the University of Strathclyde. He has done few private corporate films for the companies in UK and Denmark while he was working for Martin Professional A/S as a product design engineer.\n\nIn an interview with ''[[The Hindu]]'',<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/vinod-lingala-makes-his-directorial-debut-with-a-set-of-newcomers-in-guppedantha-prema/article8214247.ece The Hindu, Love as a Debut Vehicle]</ref> the national newspaper he shares that he explored the world, travelling around nook and corner of his favorite 15 countries, learning and experiencing people, cultures, music, history, food and traditions which broadened his mind and created a unique vision.\n\n==Career==\nComing back to India in pursuit of his film making dream, he joined Madhura Sreedhar, director and producer as an associate director for the film ''It's My Love Story'' and later worked as an assistant director [[Srikanth Addala]]  for the film ''[[Seethamma Vakitlo Sirimalle Chettu]]'' starring [[Mahesh Babu]] and [[Daggubati Venkatesh]]. His directorial debut film, ''Guppedantha Prema,'' had a very good run in the multiplexes and A-center halls and had a reasonable viewership in the towns. Poetic nature of the film was well appreciated by the viewers.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!No\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n|-\n|1 || 2016 || ''[[Guppedantha Prema]]'' || Script and director\n|-\n|2 || 2013 || ''[[Seethamma Vakitlo Sirimalle Chettu]]'' || Assistant director\n|-\n|3 || 2011 || ''It's My Love Story'' || Associate director\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RG_910LXC4Q Guppedantha Prema Teaser]\n*[[Guppedantha Prema|Guppedantha Prema Wiki Page]]\n*[http://www.celebrityprofiles.in/2016/01/guppedantha-prema-movie-first-look-released/ Guppedantha Prema First Look]\n*[http://www.idlebrain.com/movietape/guppedanthaprema.html Guppedantha Prema Teaser and Trailer] at [[Idlebrain.com]]\n*[http://www.idlebrain.com/news/today/firstlook-guppedanthaprema.html Guppedantha Prema First Look] at [[Idlebrain.com]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160404105545/http://archives.eenadu.net/02-15-2016/telugumovies/cinemanews.aspx?item=cinema&no=6 Guppedantha Prema] at [[Eenadu]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lingala, Vinod}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Telangana]]\n[[Category:Indian male writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2016}}\n{{Orphan|date=March 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n|image = \n| name = Vinod Lingala\n| birth_place = [[Warangal]], [[India]]\n| years_active = 2008-present\n| occupation = [[Film Director]], [[Screenwriter]]\n}}\n'''Vinod Lingala''' is an Indian film director and writer. He did his Masters in Practical Film making from MET Film School, London, UK. He then pursued his M.S. in Global Innovation management in The University of Strathclyde, Glasgow, United Kingdom and University of Alborg, Alborg, Denmark and worked as a Product Design Engineer for Martin Professional A/S, Denmark before he started his film career as an associate director in Indian cinema.  His directorial debut Telugu feature film ''Guppedantha Prema'' was well appreciated by critics and viewers alike.\n\n==Early life==\nVinod Lingala did his schooling in Bishop Beretta High School. He pursued his B.Tech from Kakatiya Institute of Technology and Science and later bagged a huge European Union Scholarship for Masters in Global Innovation management in the University of Strathclyde. He has done few private corporate films for the companies in UK and Denmark while he was working for Martin Professional A/S as a product design engineer.\n\nIn an interview with ''[[The Hindu]]'',<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/vinod-lingala-makes-his-directorial-debut-with-a-set-of-newcomers-in-guppedantha-prema/article8214247.ece The Hindu, Love as a Debut Vehicle]</ref> the national newspaper he shares that he explored the world, travelling around nook and corner of his favorite 15 countries, learning and experiencing people, cultures, music, history, food and traditions which broadened his mind and created a unique vision.\n\n==Career==\nComing back to India in pursuit of his film making dream, he joined Madhura Sreedhar, director and producer as an associate director for the film ''It's My Love Story'' and later worked as an assistant director [[Srikanth Addala]]  for the film ''[[Seethamma Vakitlo Sirimalle Chettu]]'' starring [[Mahesh Babu]] and [[Daggubati Venkatesh]]. His directorial debut film, ''Guppedantha Prema,'' had a very good run in the multiplexes and A-center halls and had a reasonable viewership in the towns. Poetic nature of the film was well appreciated by the viewers.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!No\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n|-\n|1 || 2016 || ''[[Guppedantha Prema]]'' || Script and director\n|-\n|2 || 2013 || ''[[Seethamma Vakitlo Sirimalle Chettu]]'' || Assistant director\n|-\n|3 || 2011 || ''It's My Love Story'' || Associate director\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RG_910LXC4Q Guppedantha Prema Teaser]\n*[[Guppedantha Prema|Guppedantha Prema Wiki Page]]\n*[http://www.celebrityprofiles.in/2016/01/guppedantha-prema-movie-first-look-released/ Guppedantha Prema First Look]\n*[http://www.idlebrain.com/movietape/guppedanthaprema.html Guppedantha Prema Teaser and Trailer] at [[Idlebrain.com]]\n*[http://www.idlebrain.com/news/today/firstlook-guppedanthaprema.html Guppedantha Prema First Look] at [[Idlebrain.com]]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160404105545/http://archives.eenadu.net/02-15-2016/telugumovies/cinemanews.aspx?item=cinema&no=6 Guppedantha Prema] at [[Eenadu]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lingala, Vinod}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Telangana]]\n[[Category:Indian male writers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vinod_Lingala"}
{"title_page": "HomePod", "text_new": "{{short description|Smart speaker designed by Apple inc}}\n{{confused|iPod|iPod Hi-Fi|AirPods}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox information appliance\n| name = HomePod\n| logo = Apple HomePod Wordmark.svg\n| logo_size = \n| image = An Apple HomePod speaker .png\n| caption = A white HomePod on display at [[WWDC 2017]]\n| developer = [[Apple Inc.]]\n| manufacturer = {{plainlist|\n*[[Inventec]]<ref name=\"Manufacturers\">{{Cite news|url=http://m.gsmarena.com/homepod_will_launch_in_q4_this_year_in_limited_quantity-news-26765.php|title=HomePod will launch in Q4 this year in limited quantity|publisher=GSMArena.com|access-date=2017-08-17|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817163739/http://m.gsmarena.com/homepod_will_launch_in_q4_this_year_in_limited_quantity-news-26765.php|archivedate=17 August 2017}}</ref> (under contract)\n*[[Foxconn]]<ref name=\"Manufacturers\" /> (under contract)\n}}\n| type = [[Smart speaker]]\n| units sold = 1-3 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2018/08/14/strategy-analytics-homepod-2q18/|title=HomePod Sales May Be Closer to 1-1.5 Million Than 3 Million Since the Speaker Launched|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2018/08/02/homepod-estimated-3-million-sales/|title=HomePod Estimated to Have 3 Million Sales and 6% Market Share in United States|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en}}</ref>\n| MSRP = {{US$}}299<br>{{CA$}}449<br>{{\u00a3}}319<br>{{A$}}499\n| os = [[tvOS]] (as of 13.4)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9to5mac.com/2020/04/13/homepod-now-runs-on-tvos-heres-what-that-could-mean/|title=HomePod now runs on tvOS, here\u2019s what that could mean|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n[[iOS]] (prior to version 13.4)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT208714|title=About iOS Software Updates for HomePod|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n| power = \n| dimensions = {{convert|6.8 x 5.6|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| soc = [[Apple A8]]\n| memory = 1&nbsp;[[Gigabyte|GB]] [[LPDDR3]] RAM\n| display = 272 x 340 [[dot matrix#LED matrix|LED matrix]]\n| storage = 16&nbsp;GB\n| input = [[Multi-touch]] [[touch screen|screen]], [[speech recognition|voice commands]] via [[Siri]]\n| sound = 7 tweeters, {{convert|4|in|cm|adj=on}} woofer, 6 microphones\n| weight = {{convert|5.5|lb|kg|abbr=on}}\n| related = \n| connectivity = 802.11a/b/g/n/ac [[Wi\u2011Fi]] with [[MIMO]]<br>[[Bluetooth 5.0]]<br>Direct peer-to-peer access from [[iPhone 5S]] or later; [[iPad Pro]], [[iPad (2017)]], [[iPad Air]], [[iPad Mini]] 2 or later, or [[iPod Touch (6th generation)]], devices running iOS 12 or later<ref>{{cite web |title=HomePod - Technical Specifications - Apple |url=https://www.apple.com/homepod/specs/ |accessdate=14 August 2019}}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|https://apple.com/homepod/}}\n| releasedate = {{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0; |title={{start date and age|2018|2|9|df=y|br=y|paren=y}}\n|Australia\n|United Kingdom\n|United States\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0; |title={{start date and age|2018|6|18|df=y|br=y|paren=y}}\n|Canada\n|France\n|Germany\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0; |title={{start date and age|2018|10|26|df=y|br=y|paren=y}}\n|Mexico\n|Spain\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0; |title={{start date and age|2019|1|18|df=y|br=y|paren=y}}\n|Mainland China\n|Hong Kong\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0; |title={{start date and age|2019|8|23|df=y|br=y|paren=y}}\n|Japan\n|Taiwan\n}}\n}}\n\n'''HomePod''' is a [[smart speaker]] developed by [[Apple Inc.]], the company's second [[Apple speakers|speaker]] after the [[iPod Hi-Fi]]. Announced on 5 June 2017, at the [[Apple Worldwide Developers Conference]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/5/15732144/apple-homepod-speaker-announced-siri-price-release-date-wwdc-2017|title=Apple announces HomePod speaker to take on Sonos|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=2017-06-05|website=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2017-06-05|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605203335/https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/5/15732144/apple-homepod-speaker-announced-siri-price-release-date-wwdc-2017|archivedate=5 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Meet HomePod\">{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2017/06/05/apple-wwdc-2017-apple-homepod/|title=Meet Apple's Echo Rival, Homepod|work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|access-date=2017-11-18|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117172117/http://fortune.com/2017/06/05/apple-wwdc-2017-apple-homepod/|archivedate=17 November 2017}}</ref> its launch was later delayed from December 2017 to early 2018.<ref name=\"Meet HomePod\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/17/16670268/apple-homepod-delayed-2018|title=Apple's HomePod delayed until next year|work=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2017-11-17|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117230114/https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/17/16670268/apple-homepod-delayed-2018|archivedate=17 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/11/17/apple-delays-homepod-speaker-launch-to-early-2018/|title=Apple delays HomePod smart speaker until early 2018|work=[[Engadget]]|accessdate=2017-11-17|date=2017-11-17|first=Jon|last=Fingas|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118051330/https://www.engadget.com/2017/11/17/apple-delays-homepod-speaker-launch-to-early-2018/|archivedate=18 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-delays-homepod-speaker-to-2018/|title=Apple delays HomePod to 2018|publisher=[[CNET]]|access-date=2017-11-17|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118084559/https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-delays-homepod-speaker-to-2018/|archivedate=18 November 2017}}</ref> Apple began taking orders on 26 January 2018,<ref>{{cite press release|title=HomePod arrives February 9, available to order this Friday|url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2018/01/homepod-arrives-february-9-available-to-order-this-friday/|publisher=[[Apple Inc.]]|accessdate=2018-01-23|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123140524/https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2018/01/homepod-arrives-february-9-available-to-order-this-friday/|archivedate=23 January 2018}}</ref> and formally released it on 9 February 2018. \n\nDesigned to accompany other Apple products such as the [[iPhone]] and [[Macintosh|Mac]], the HomePod is designed to work with [[Apple Music]] to create a \"new way for you to discover and interact with music at home,\" according to Apple marketers.<ref>Apple inc. [https://www.apple.com/homepod/ HomePod - Apple.] Retrieved 2 February 2019</ref> It incorporates [[beamforming]] and eight speakers<ref name=\"verge-review\"/> and is sold in two colors: White and Space Gray.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imore.com/homepod-faq|title=Everything about HomePod|website=[[iMore]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620010142/https://www.imore.com/homepod-faq|archive-date=20 June 2017|url-status=live|access-date=2017-06-19}}</ref>\n\nThe HomePod received mixed reviews: it was praised for its design and sound quality compared to other speakers of its price, and criticized for lack of third-party support and high price compared to other smart speakers. As well, the silicone base on the bottom of the device was found to occasionally damage wooden surfaces. As of August 2018, the HomePod had sold an estimated 1 to 3 million units.\n\n==Specifications==\nThe HomePod has a rounded, cylindrical shape, and has a small touchscreen on its top. It has seven [[tweeter]]s in its base and a four-inch [[woofer]] (Apple does not specify Hz frequency range) towards the top, as well as six [[microphone]]s used for [[voice control]] and acoustic optimization.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/12/17003296/homepod-repair-ifixit-teardown|title=This iFixit teardown shows the HomePod is built like a tank|work=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2018-02-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212212259/https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/12/17003296/homepod-repair-ifixit-teardown|archivedate=12 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/31/16067710/apple-leaked-homepod-firmware-os-third-party-apps|title=HomePod firmware reveals more secrets of Apple's smart speaker|last=Ong|first=Thuy|date=2017-07-31|website=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2017-09-03|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904063324/https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/31/16067710/apple-leaked-homepod-firmware-os-third-party-apps|archivedate=4 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"wired-review\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/review/review-apple-homepod/|title=HomePod Review: Only Apple Devotees Need Apply|website=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215083738/https://www.wired.com/review/review-apple-homepod/|archivedate=15 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wadav.com/tech/apple-home-pod-review|title=Apple Home Pod Review|website=www.wadav.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-02}}</ref>\n\nThe device runs a version of the [[tvOS]] (though it was a version of [[iOS]] prior to version 13.4) operating system specifically designed for the HomePod speaker to play audio, run the [[Siri]] voice assistant and control the device's screen. The processor featured in the HomePod is an [[Apple A8]] system-on-chip, which had been included in some prior Apple products.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"wired-review\" /> Siri can be used to control the speaker and other [[HomeKit]] devices, and can be used to conduct text messaging and voice calls from an iPhone. The HomePod mainly supports Apple's own platforms and technologies, including [[Apple Music]], [[iTunes Store]] purchases and [[iTunes Match|Match]], iTunes podcasts, [[Beats 1]] radio, and [[AirPlay]] (with limited third-party support for internet radio services [[iHeartRadio]], [[Radio.com]], and [[TuneIn]] coming in the fall of 2019), while an [[iOS 11]] device is required for initial setup. HomePod can serve as a sound bar within a home entertainment system when selected through an Apple TV. The HomePod does not officially support audio-in from [[Bluetooth]] sources.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/02/apple-clarifies-which-audio-sources-are-supported-on-homepod-speakers/|title=Apple clarifies which audio sources are supported on HomePod speakers|work=[[Ars Technica]]|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215023704/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/02/apple-clarifies-which-audio-sources-are-supported-on-homepod-speakers/|archivedate=15 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"wired-review\" /> Andrew Faden has developed a solution he calls \"BabelPod\" to allow [[line level#Line in|line in]] and Bluetooth input to the HomePod through the use of a [[Raspberry Pi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://faden.me/2018/03/18/babelpod.html|title=BabelPod: Line-In and Bluetooth Input for HomePod|website=faden.me|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322143005/http://faden.me/2018/03/18/babelpod.html|archivedate=22 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nAirPlay 2 and multi-room, multi-speaker support were announced in February 2018, and released in September 2018 in iOS 12 along with additional features such as multiple named timers, Find my iPhone, Siri shortcuts, the ability to make, receive and screen phone calls directly on the HomePod, and the ability to search for songs using the lyrics.<ref name=\":1\" /> HomePod initially lacked support for allowing multiple users to use the device<ref name=\"ars-review\" />, but it was later announced that multi-user support would be added in iOS 13 when it's released in the fall of 2019.{{update after|2019|10|1}}\n\nThe 13.4 software update, which released in March of 2020, updated the OS from an iOS code base to a tvOS based system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2020/04/13/homepod-tvos-operating-system/|title=HomePod Operating System Now Based on tvOS Instead of iOS Amid Rumors of Smaller HomePod|last=Clover|first=Juli|date=April 13, 2020|website=MacRumors|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Due to Apple's pairing of software resources to hardware architecture, the update was meant to be seamless to the majority of users.\n\n[[greenhouse gas#Direct greenhouse gas emissions|Greenhouse gas emissions]] for production, expected use and recycling for the HomePod are estimated at 146&nbsp;kg&nbsp;[[carbon dioxide equivalent|CO<sub>2</sub>e]].<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2018-01-26|title=HomePod Environmental Report|url=https://images.apple.com/environment/pdf/products/homepod/HomePod_PER_feb2018.pdf|journal=Apple and the Environment|publisher=[[Apple Inc.]]|format=[[PDF]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216204441/https://images.apple.com/environment/pdf/products/homepod/HomePod_PER_feb2018.pdf|archivedate=16 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nThe HomePod received mixed reviews. The review from ''[[The Verge]]'' praised the HomePod's automatic acoustic calibration system, and felt that it sounded \"noticeably richer and fuller\" than competitors such as the [[Sonos One]] (described as sounding \"a little empty\") and [[Google Home|Google Home Max]] (described as being a \"bass-heavy mess\").<ref name=\"verge-review\"/> The review from ''[[Ars Technica]]'' stated that the sound quality of the HomePod was \"pretty good, rich and full for its size, better than the Sonos One but probably not $150 better, [and] a galaxy ahead of the [[Amazon Echo|Echo]].\"<ref name=\"ars-review\"/>\n\nIts lack of support for third-party services and platforms was criticized,<ref name=\"wired-review\" /><ref name=\"ars-review\"/><ref name=\"verge-review\"/> with ''Ars Technica'' arguing that it gave the device \"intense inflexibility\".<ref name=\"ars-review\">{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/02/review-apples-homepod-is-a-fun-apple-music-accessory-and-thats-it/|title=Apple\u2019s HomePod: Paying $350 for a speaker that says \u201cno\u201d this much is tough|work=[[Ars Technica]]|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214174105/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/02/review-apples-homepod-is-a-fun-apple-music-accessory-and-thats-it/|archivedate=14 February 2018}}</ref> Siri on the HomePod was also criticized for its limited functionality in comparison to assistants such as [[Amazon Alexa|Alexa]] and [[Google Assistant]]; ''The Verge'' cited the inability to actually place phone calls from the speaker (they must be made on an iPhone and transferred to the HomePod), set multiple [[timer]]s at once, or distinguish between multiple voices, and only supporting basic commands when using AirPlay, among other limitations.<ref name=\"verge-review\"/><ref name=\"wired-review\" /> Multiple [[reminders (Apple)|reminders]] can be used in lieu of multiple timers, albeit with less precision than a timer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leancrew.com/all-this/2018/02/friendly-reminders/|title=Friendly reminders|author=Dr. Drang|work=And now it\u2019s all this|publisher=leancrew|date=2018-02-15|access-date=2018-04-10|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309142647/http://leancrew.com/all-this/2018/02/friendly-reminders/|archivedate=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://leancrew.com/all-this/2018/02/timers-reminders-alarms-oh-my/|title=Timers, reminders, alarms \u2014 oh, my!|author=Dr. Drang|work=And now it\u2019s all this|publisher=leancrew|date=2018-02-17|access-date=2018-04-10|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226231612/http://leancrew.com/all-this/2018/02/timers-reminders-alarms-oh-my/|archivedate=26 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://daringfireball.net/linked/2018/02/26/dr-drang-timers-reminders-alerts|title=Timers, Reminders, and Alarms on Apple Devices|work=[[Daring Fireball]]|first=John|last=Gruber|authorlink=John Gruber|date=2018-02-26|access-date=2018-04-10|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411025945/https://daringfireball.net/linked/2018/02/26/dr-drang-timers-reminders-alerts|archivedate=11 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.loopinsight.com/2018/02/28/timers-reminders-alarms-oh-my/|work=The Loop|title=Timers, reminders, alarms\u2014oh, my!|date=2018-02-28|access-date=2018-04-10|first=Dave|last=Mark|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411025942/http://www.loopinsight.com/2018/02/28/timers-reminders-alarms-oh-my/|archivedate=11 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lifehacker.com/how-to-deal-with-apple-s-inconsistent-alerts-system-1823355397|title=How to deal with Apple's inconsistent alerts system|work=[[Lifehacker]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411025924/https://lifehacker.com/how-to-deal-with-apple-s-inconsistent-alerts-system-1823355397|archivedate=11 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pxlnv.com/linklog/timers-reminders-alarms/|title=Timers, Reminders, and Alarms \u2014 Pixel Envy|first=Nick|last=Heer|website=pxlnv.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411025931/https://pxlnv.com/linklog/timers-reminders-alarms/|archivedate=11 April 2018}}</ref> All these issues have been fixed in [[iOS]] 12, released on 17 September 2018.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://tidbits.com/2018/09/24/apple-updates-homepod-with-ios-12-for-phone-calls-multiple-timers-and-more/|title=Apple Updates HomePod with iOS 12 for Phone Calls, Multiple Timers, and More|first=Adam|last=Engst|date=2018-09-24|access-date=2019-01-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''The Verge'' gave HomePod a 7.5 out of 10, arguing that it \"does more to make music sound better than any other speaker of this kind has ever done before\", but that consumers should consider other options \"unless you live entirely inside Apple's [[closed platform|walled garden]] and prioritize sound quality over everything else.\"<ref name=\"verge-review\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/6/16976906/apple-homepod-review-smart-speaker|title=Apple HomePod review: locked in|work=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2018-02-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213060549/https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/6/16976906/apple-homepod-review-smart-speaker|archivedate=13 February 2018}}</ref> ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' shared similar criticisms over its lack of Siri functionality and support for third-party services, concluding that the HomePod would be of little interest to those who are not heavily invested in Apple's software and hardware ecosystem.<ref name=\"wired-review\" />\n\nIt was reported by some owners that the HomePod's silicone base stained oiled wooden surfaces with a white \"ring\" mark.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-43064772|title=Apple's HomePod speakers mark wood|date=2018-02-14|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214224644/http://www.bbc.com/news/technology-43064772|archivedate=14 February 2018}}</ref> Although Apple states that \"it is not unusual for any speaker with a vibration-dampening silicone base to leave mild marks when placed on some wooden surfaces\", and that the marks would eventually \"improve\" on its own, Stuart Miles (founder of the British technology blog ''Pocket-lint'') reported that in his experience, the stain occurred after only about 20 minutes of use on a wooden surface, and that he had to sand and re-oil the surface to remove it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pocket-lint.com/smart-home/reviews/apple/141256-apple-homepod-review|title=Apple HomePod review: The smart sounding speaker that's just not smart enough - Pocket-lint|website=www.pocket-lint.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322143444/https://www.pocket-lint.com/smart-home/reviews/apple/141256-apple-homepod-review|archivedate=22 March 2018}}</ref> [[John Gruber]] criticized Apple for this abnormality, remarking that he had never seen an Apple product damage surfaces in such a manner before, and that it \"seems like an issue that should have been caught during the period where HomePod was being widely tested at home by many Apple employees.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://daringfireball.net/linked/2018/02/14/homepod-wood-furniture-rings | title=HomePod Can Damage Wood Furniture | date=2018-02-14 | first=John | last=Gruber | authorlink=John Gruber | work=[[Daring Fireball]] | accessdate=2018-03-21 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322082228/https://daringfireball.net/linked/2018/02/14/homepod-wood-furniture-rings | archivedate=22 March 2018 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Sales ==\nStrategy Analytics estimated that 600,000 HomePods were sold in first quarter of 2018, making Apple the fourth best selling smart speaker brand after [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Google]] and [[Alibaba Group|Alibaba]], giving Apple a 6% market share in the industry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20180517006158/en/Strategy-Analytics-Amazon's-Global-Smart-Speaker-Share/|title=Strategy Analytics: Amazon\u2019s Global Smart Speaker Share Falls Below 50% in Q1 2018 as Competition Heats Up|access-date=2018-05-18|language=en}}</ref> The HomePod also has 6% market share in the United States according to a report from Consumer  Intelligence Research Partners and sold an estimated 700,000 units worldwide in the second quarter of 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2018/08/18/apple-market-share-smart-speaker-google-amazon/37458353/|title=Apple gains a foothold in the smart speaker market: A Foolish Take|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=2018-08-18|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20180813005370/en/Strategy-Analytics-Google-Closes-Gap-Amazon-Global|title=Strategy Analytics: Google Closes Gap on Amazon in Global Smart Speaker Market in Q2 2018|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en}}</ref> Also in the second quarter of 2018, Strategy Analytics estimated that the HomePod outsold all smart speakers that cost more than $200, giving Apple a 70% market share in premium brand smart speakers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://9to5mac.com/2018/09/19/homepod-takes-majority-of-premium-sales/|title=HomePod misses top 5 smart speaker list, but grabs impressive 70% of $200+ market|date=2018-09-19|work=[[9to5Mac]]|access-date=2018-10-05|language=en-US}}</ref>  As of mid 2018, the HomePod had sold an estimated 3 million units.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2018/08/02/homepod-estimated-3-million-sales/|title=HomePod Estimated to Have 3 Million Sales and 6% Market Share in United States|access-date=2018-10-05|language=en}}</ref> Sales increased 45% in Q4 2018, with Apple selling 1.6 million units that quarter. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.idropnews.com/news/homepod-sales-grew-45-percent-over-holiday-quarter-but-actually-lost-market-share/97172/|title=HomePod Sales Grew 45 Percent Over Holiday Quarter, But Actually Lost Market Share|date=2019-02-20|website=iDrop News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-30}}</ref> In April 2019, Apple reduced the price to USD $299.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/4/4/18295084/apple-homepod-price-cut-299-smart-speaker|title=Apple drops HomePod price down to $299|work=[[The Verge]]|last=Gartenberg|first=Chris|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|https://www.apple.com/homepod/}}\n* [https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2017/06/homepod-reinvents-music-in-the-home/ Apple press release]\n\n{{Apple hardware}}\n{{iOS}}\n{{Apple hardware since 1998}}\n{{Apple Inc.}}\n{{Smart speaker}}\n\n[[Category:Apple Inc. hardware]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 2017]]\n[[Category:Smart speakers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Smart speaker designed by Apple inc}}\n{{confused|iPod|iPod Hi-Fi|AirPods}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox information appliance\n| name = HomePod\n| logo = Apple HomePod Wordmark.svg\n| logo_size = \n| image = An Apple HomePod speaker .png\n| caption = A white HomePod on display at [[WWDC 2017]]\n| developer = [[Apple Inc.]]\n| manufacturer = {{plainlist|\n*[[Inventec]]<ref name=\"Manufacturers\">{{Cite news|url=http://m.gsmarena.com/homepod_will_launch_in_q4_this_year_in_limited_quantity-news-26765.php|title=HomePod will launch in Q4 this year in limited quantity|publisher=GSMArena.com|access-date=2017-08-17|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170817163739/http://m.gsmarena.com/homepod_will_launch_in_q4_this_year_in_limited_quantity-news-26765.php|archivedate=17 August 2017}}</ref> (under contract)\n*[[Foxconn]]<ref name=\"Manufacturers\" /> (under contract)\n}}\n| type = [[Smart speaker]]\n| units sold = 1-3 million<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2018/08/14/strategy-analytics-homepod-2q18/|title=HomePod Sales May Be Closer to 1-1.5 Million Than 3 Million Since the Speaker Launched|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2018/08/02/homepod-estimated-3-million-sales/|title=HomePod Estimated to Have 3 Million Sales and 6% Market Share in United States|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en}}</ref>\n| MSRP = {{US$}}349<br>{{CA$}}449<br>{{\u00a3}}319<br>{{A$}}499\n| os = [[tvOS]] (as of 13.4)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9to5mac.com/2020/04/13/homepod-now-runs-on-tvos-heres-what-that-could-mean/|title=HomePod now runs on tvOS, here\u2019s what that could mean|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n[[iOS]] (prior to version 13.4)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://support.apple.com/en-us/HT208714|title=About iOS Software Updates for HomePod|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n| power = \n| dimensions = {{convert|6.8 x 5.6|in|mm|abbr=on}}\n| soc = [[Apple A8]]\n| memory = 1&nbsp;[[Gigabyte|GB]] [[LPDDR3]] RAM\n| display = 272 x 340 [[dot matrix#LED matrix|LED matrix]]\n| storage = 16&nbsp;GB\n| input = [[Multi-touch]] [[touch screen|screen]], [[speech recognition|voice commands]] via [[Siri]]\n| sound = 7 tweeters, {{convert|4|in|cm|adj=on}} woofer, 6 microphones\n| weight = {{convert|5.5|lb|kg|abbr=on}}\n| related = \n| connectivity = 802.11a/b/g/n/ac [[Wi\u2011Fi]] with [[MIMO]]<br>[[Bluetooth 5.0]]<br>Direct peer-to-peer access from [[iPhone 5S]] or later; [[iPad Pro]], [[iPad (2017)]], [[iPad Air]], [[iPad Mini]] 2 or later, or [[iPod Touch (6th generation)]], devices running iOS 12 or later<ref>{{cite web |title=HomePod - Technical Specifications - Apple |url=https://www.apple.com/homepod/specs/ |accessdate=14 August 2019}}</ref>\n| website = {{URL|https://apple.com/homepod/}}\n| releasedate = {{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0; |title={{start date and age|2018|2|9|df=y|br=y|paren=y}}\n|Australia\n|United Kingdom\n|United States\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0; |title={{start date and age|2018|6|18|df=y|br=y|paren=y}}\n|Canada\n|France\n|Germany\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0; |title={{start date and age|2018|10|26|df=y|br=y|paren=y}}\n|Mexico\n|Spain\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0; |title={{start date and age|2019|1|18|df=y|br=y|paren=y}}\n|Mainland China\n|Hong Kong\n}}\n{{Collapsible list|framestyle=border:none; padding:0; |title={{start date and age|2019|8|23|df=y|br=y|paren=y}}\n|Japan\n|Taiwan\n}}\n}}\n\n'''HomePod''' is a [[smart speaker]] developed by [[Apple Inc.]], the company's second [[Apple speakers|speaker]] after the [[iPod Hi-Fi]]. Announced on 5 June 2017, at the [[Apple Worldwide Developers Conference]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/5/15732144/apple-homepod-speaker-announced-siri-price-release-date-wwdc-2017|title=Apple announces HomePod speaker to take on Sonos|last=Gartenberg|first=Chaim|date=2017-06-05|website=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2017-06-05|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170605203335/https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/5/15732144/apple-homepod-speaker-announced-siri-price-release-date-wwdc-2017|archivedate=5 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Meet HomePod\">{{Cite news|url=http://fortune.com/2017/06/05/apple-wwdc-2017-apple-homepod/|title=Meet Apple's Echo Rival, Homepod|work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|access-date=2017-11-18|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117172117/http://fortune.com/2017/06/05/apple-wwdc-2017-apple-homepod/|archivedate=17 November 2017}}</ref> its launch was later delayed from December 2017 to early 2018.<ref name=\"Meet HomePod\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/17/16670268/apple-homepod-delayed-2018|title=Apple's HomePod delayed until next year|work=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2017-11-17|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171117230114/https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/17/16670268/apple-homepod-delayed-2018|archivedate=17 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/11/17/apple-delays-homepod-speaker-launch-to-early-2018/|title=Apple delays HomePod smart speaker until early 2018|work=[[Engadget]]|accessdate=2017-11-17|date=2017-11-17|first=Jon|last=Fingas|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118051330/https://www.engadget.com/2017/11/17/apple-delays-homepod-speaker-launch-to-early-2018/|archivedate=18 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-delays-homepod-speaker-to-2018/|title=Apple delays HomePod to 2018|publisher=[[CNET]]|access-date=2017-11-17|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118084559/https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-delays-homepod-speaker-to-2018/|archivedate=18 November 2017}}</ref> Apple began taking orders on 26 January 2018,<ref>{{cite press release|title=HomePod arrives February 9, available to order this Friday|url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2018/01/homepod-arrives-february-9-available-to-order-this-friday/|publisher=[[Apple Inc.]]|accessdate=2018-01-23|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123140524/https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2018/01/homepod-arrives-february-9-available-to-order-this-friday/|archivedate=23 January 2018}}</ref> and formally released it on 9 February 2018. \n\nDesigned to accompany other Apple products such as the [[iPhone]] and [[Macintosh|Mac]], the HomePod is designed to work with [[Apple Music]] to create a \"new way for you to discover and interact with music at home,\" according to Apple marketers.<ref>Apple inc. [https://www.apple.com/homepod/ HomePod - Apple.] Retrieved 2 February 2019</ref> It incorporates [[beamforming]] and eight speakers<ref name=\"verge-review\"/> and is sold in two colors: White and Space Gray.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imore.com/homepod-faq|title=Everything about HomePod|website=[[iMore]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170620010142/https://www.imore.com/homepod-faq|archive-date=20 June 2017|url-status=live|access-date=2017-06-19}}</ref>\n\nThe HomePod received mixed reviews: it was praised for its design and sound quality compared to other speakers of its price, and criticized for lack of third-party support and high price compared to other smart speakers. As well, the silicone base on the bottom of the device was found to occasionally damage wooden surfaces. As of August 2018, the HomePod had sold an estimated 1 to 3 million units.\n\n==Specifications==\nThe HomePod has a rounded, cylindrical shape, and has a small touchscreen on its top. It has seven [[tweeter]]s in its base and a four-inch [[woofer]] (Apple does not specify Hz frequency range) towards the top, as well as six [[microphone]]s used for [[voice control]] and acoustic optimization.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/12/17003296/homepod-repair-ifixit-teardown|title=This iFixit teardown shows the HomePod is built like a tank|work=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2018-02-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212212259/https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/12/17003296/homepod-repair-ifixit-teardown|archivedate=12 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/31/16067710/apple-leaked-homepod-firmware-os-third-party-apps|title=HomePod firmware reveals more secrets of Apple's smart speaker|last=Ong|first=Thuy|date=2017-07-31|website=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2017-09-03|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170904063324/https://www.theverge.com/2017/7/31/16067710/apple-leaked-homepod-firmware-os-third-party-apps|archivedate=4 September 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"wired-review\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/review/review-apple-homepod/|title=HomePod Review: Only Apple Devotees Need Apply|website=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|language=en-US|access-date=2018-02-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215083738/https://www.wired.com/review/review-apple-homepod/|archivedate=15 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wadav.com/tech/apple-home-pod-review|title=Apple Home Pod Review|website=www.wadav.com|language=en|access-date=2018-08-02}}</ref>\n\nThe device runs a version of the [[tvOS]] (though it was a version of [[iOS]] prior to version 13.4) operating system specifically designed for the HomePod speaker to play audio, run the [[Siri]] voice assistant and control the device's screen. The processor featured in the HomePod is an [[Apple A8]] system-on-chip, which had been included in some prior Apple products.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"wired-review\" /> Siri can be used to control the speaker and other [[HomeKit]] devices, and can be used to conduct text messaging and voice calls from an iPhone. The HomePod mainly supports Apple's own platforms and technologies, including [[Apple Music]], [[iTunes Store]] purchases and [[iTunes Match|Match]], iTunes podcasts, [[Beats 1]] radio, and [[AirPlay]] (with limited third-party support for internet radio services [[iHeartRadio]], [[Radio.com]], and [[TuneIn]] coming in the fall of 2019), while an [[iOS 11]] device is required for initial setup. HomePod can serve as a sound bar within a home entertainment system when selected through an Apple TV. The HomePod does not officially support audio-in from [[Bluetooth]] sources.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/02/apple-clarifies-which-audio-sources-are-supported-on-homepod-speakers/|title=Apple clarifies which audio sources are supported on HomePod speakers|work=[[Ars Technica]]|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180215023704/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/02/apple-clarifies-which-audio-sources-are-supported-on-homepod-speakers/|archivedate=15 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"wired-review\" /> Andrew Faden has developed a solution he calls \"BabelPod\" to allow [[line level#Line in|line in]] and Bluetooth input to the HomePod through the use of a [[Raspberry Pi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://faden.me/2018/03/18/babelpod.html|title=BabelPod: Line-In and Bluetooth Input for HomePod|website=faden.me|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322143005/http://faden.me/2018/03/18/babelpod.html|archivedate=22 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nAirPlay 2 and multi-room, multi-speaker support were announced in February 2018, and released in September 2018 in iOS 12 along with additional features such as multiple named timers, Find my iPhone, Siri shortcuts, the ability to make, receive and screen phone calls directly on the HomePod, and the ability to search for songs using the lyrics.<ref name=\":1\" /> HomePod initially lacked support for allowing multiple users to use the device<ref name=\"ars-review\" />, but it was later announced that multi-user support would be added in iOS 13 when it's released in the fall of 2019.{{update after|2019|10|1}}\n\nThe 13.4 software update, which released in March of 2020, updated the OS from an iOS code base to a tvOS based system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2020/04/13/homepod-tvos-operating-system/|title=HomePod Operating System Now Based on tvOS Instead of iOS Amid Rumors of Smaller HomePod|last=Clover|first=Juli|date=April 13, 2020|website=MacRumors|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Due to Apple's pairing of software resources to hardware architecture, the update was meant to be seamless to the majority of users.\n\n[[greenhouse gas#Direct greenhouse gas emissions|Greenhouse gas emissions]] for production, expected use and recycling for the HomePod are estimated at 146&nbsp;kg&nbsp;[[carbon dioxide equivalent|CO<sub>2</sub>e]].<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2018-01-26|title=HomePod Environmental Report|url=https://images.apple.com/environment/pdf/products/homepod/HomePod_PER_feb2018.pdf|journal=Apple and the Environment|publisher=[[Apple Inc.]]|format=[[PDF]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180216204441/https://images.apple.com/environment/pdf/products/homepod/HomePod_PER_feb2018.pdf|archivedate=16 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nThe HomePod received mixed reviews. The review from ''[[The Verge]]'' praised the HomePod's automatic acoustic calibration system, and felt that it sounded \"noticeably richer and fuller\" than competitors such as the [[Sonos One]] (described as sounding \"a little empty\") and [[Google Home|Google Home Max]] (described as being a \"bass-heavy mess\").<ref name=\"verge-review\"/> The review from ''[[Ars Technica]]'' stated that the sound quality of the HomePod was \"pretty good, rich and full for its size, better than the Sonos One but probably not $150 better, [and] a galaxy ahead of the [[Amazon Echo|Echo]].\"<ref name=\"ars-review\"/>\n\nIts lack of support for third-party services and platforms was criticized,<ref name=\"wired-review\" /><ref name=\"ars-review\"/><ref name=\"verge-review\"/> with ''Ars Technica'' arguing that it gave the device \"intense inflexibility\".<ref name=\"ars-review\">{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/02/review-apples-homepod-is-a-fun-apple-music-accessory-and-thats-it/|title=Apple\u2019s HomePod: Paying $350 for a speaker that says \u201cno\u201d this much is tough|work=[[Ars Technica]]|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-us|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214174105/https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/02/review-apples-homepod-is-a-fun-apple-music-accessory-and-thats-it/|archivedate=14 February 2018}}</ref> Siri on the HomePod was also criticized for its limited functionality in comparison to assistants such as [[Amazon Alexa|Alexa]] and [[Google Assistant]]; ''The Verge'' cited the inability to actually place phone calls from the speaker (they must be made on an iPhone and transferred to the HomePod), set multiple [[timer]]s at once, or distinguish between multiple voices, and only supporting basic commands when using AirPlay, among other limitations.<ref name=\"verge-review\"/><ref name=\"wired-review\" /> Multiple [[reminders (Apple)|reminders]] can be used in lieu of multiple timers, albeit with less precision than a timer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://leancrew.com/all-this/2018/02/friendly-reminders/|title=Friendly reminders|author=Dr. Drang|work=And now it\u2019s all this|publisher=leancrew|date=2018-02-15|access-date=2018-04-10|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180309142647/http://leancrew.com/all-this/2018/02/friendly-reminders/|archivedate=9 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://leancrew.com/all-this/2018/02/timers-reminders-alarms-oh-my/|title=Timers, reminders, alarms \u2014 oh, my!|author=Dr. Drang|work=And now it\u2019s all this|publisher=leancrew|date=2018-02-17|access-date=2018-04-10|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180226231612/http://leancrew.com/all-this/2018/02/timers-reminders-alarms-oh-my/|archivedate=26 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://daringfireball.net/linked/2018/02/26/dr-drang-timers-reminders-alerts|title=Timers, Reminders, and Alarms on Apple Devices|work=[[Daring Fireball]]|first=John|last=Gruber|authorlink=John Gruber|date=2018-02-26|access-date=2018-04-10|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411025945/https://daringfireball.net/linked/2018/02/26/dr-drang-timers-reminders-alerts|archivedate=11 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.loopinsight.com/2018/02/28/timers-reminders-alarms-oh-my/|work=The Loop|title=Timers, reminders, alarms\u2014oh, my!|date=2018-02-28|access-date=2018-04-10|first=Dave|last=Mark|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411025942/http://www.loopinsight.com/2018/02/28/timers-reminders-alarms-oh-my/|archivedate=11 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://lifehacker.com/how-to-deal-with-apple-s-inconsistent-alerts-system-1823355397|title=How to deal with Apple's inconsistent alerts system|work=[[Lifehacker]]|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411025924/https://lifehacker.com/how-to-deal-with-apple-s-inconsistent-alerts-system-1823355397|archivedate=11 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://pxlnv.com/linklog/timers-reminders-alarms/|title=Timers, Reminders, and Alarms \u2014 Pixel Envy|first=Nick|last=Heer|website=pxlnv.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180411025931/https://pxlnv.com/linklog/timers-reminders-alarms/|archivedate=11 April 2018}}</ref> All these issues have been fixed in [[iOS]] 12, released on 17 September 2018.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=https://tidbits.com/2018/09/24/apple-updates-homepod-with-ios-12-for-phone-calls-multiple-timers-and-more/|title=Apple Updates HomePod with iOS 12 for Phone Calls, Multiple Timers, and More|first=Adam|last=Engst|date=2018-09-24|access-date=2019-01-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n''The Verge'' gave HomePod a 7.5 out of 10, arguing that it \"does more to make music sound better than any other speaker of this kind has ever done before\", but that consumers should consider other options \"unless you live entirely inside Apple's [[closed platform|walled garden]] and prioritize sound quality over everything else.\"<ref name=\"verge-review\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/6/16976906/apple-homepod-review-smart-speaker|title=Apple HomePod review: locked in|work=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2018-02-14|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180213060549/https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/6/16976906/apple-homepod-review-smart-speaker|archivedate=13 February 2018}}</ref> ''[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]'' shared similar criticisms over its lack of Siri functionality and support for third-party services, concluding that the HomePod would be of little interest to those who are not heavily invested in Apple's software and hardware ecosystem.<ref name=\"wired-review\" />\n\nIt was reported by some owners that the HomePod's silicone base stained oiled wooden surfaces with a white \"ring\" mark.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-43064772|title=Apple's HomePod speakers mark wood|date=2018-02-14|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=2018-02-14|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180214224644/http://www.bbc.com/news/technology-43064772|archivedate=14 February 2018}}</ref> Although Apple states that \"it is not unusual for any speaker with a vibration-dampening silicone base to leave mild marks when placed on some wooden surfaces\", and that the marks would eventually \"improve\" on its own, Stuart Miles (founder of the British technology blog ''Pocket-lint'') reported that in his experience, the stain occurred after only about 20 minutes of use on a wooden surface, and that he had to sand and re-oil the surface to remove it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pocket-lint.com/smart-home/reviews/apple/141256-apple-homepod-review|title=Apple HomePod review: The smart sounding speaker that's just not smart enough - Pocket-lint|website=www.pocket-lint.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322143444/https://www.pocket-lint.com/smart-home/reviews/apple/141256-apple-homepod-review|archivedate=22 March 2018}}</ref> [[John Gruber]] criticized Apple for this abnormality, remarking that he had never seen an Apple product damage surfaces in such a manner before, and that it \"seems like an issue that should have been caught during the period where HomePod was being widely tested at home by many Apple employees.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://daringfireball.net/linked/2018/02/14/homepod-wood-furniture-rings | title=HomePod Can Damage Wood Furniture | date=2018-02-14 | first=John | last=Gruber | authorlink=John Gruber | work=[[Daring Fireball]] | accessdate=2018-03-21 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180322082228/https://daringfireball.net/linked/2018/02/14/homepod-wood-furniture-rings | archivedate=22 March 2018 | df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n== Sales ==\nStrategy Analytics estimated that 600,000 HomePods were sold in first quarter of 2018, making Apple the fourth best selling smart speaker brand after [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]], [[Google]] and [[Alibaba Group|Alibaba]], giving Apple a 6% market share in the industry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20180517006158/en/Strategy-Analytics-Amazon's-Global-Smart-Speaker-Share/|title=Strategy Analytics: Amazon\u2019s Global Smart Speaker Share Falls Below 50% in Q1 2018 as Competition Heats Up|access-date=2018-05-18|language=en}}</ref> The HomePod also has 6% market share in the United States according to a report from Consumer  Intelligence Research Partners and sold an estimated 700,000 units worldwide in the second quarter of 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/news/2018/08/18/apple-market-share-smart-speaker-google-amazon/37458353/|title=Apple gains a foothold in the smart speaker market: A Foolish Take|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=2018-08-18|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20180813005370/en/Strategy-Analytics-Google-Closes-Gap-Amazon-Global|title=Strategy Analytics: Google Closes Gap on Amazon in Global Smart Speaker Market in Q2 2018|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en}}</ref> Also in the second quarter of 2018, Strategy Analytics estimated that the HomePod outsold all smart speakers that cost more than $200, giving Apple a 70% market share in premium brand smart speakers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://9to5mac.com/2018/09/19/homepod-takes-majority-of-premium-sales/|title=HomePod misses top 5 smart speaker list, but grabs impressive 70% of $200+ market|date=2018-09-19|work=[[9to5Mac]]|access-date=2018-10-05|language=en-US}}</ref>  As of mid 2018, the HomePod had sold an estimated 3 million units.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.macrumors.com/2018/08/02/homepod-estimated-3-million-sales/|title=HomePod Estimated to Have 3 Million Sales and 6% Market Share in United States|access-date=2018-10-05|language=en}}</ref> Sales increased 45% in Q4 2018, with Apple selling 1.6 million units that quarter. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.idropnews.com/news/homepod-sales-grew-45-percent-over-holiday-quarter-but-actually-lost-market-share/97172/|title=HomePod Sales Grew 45 Percent Over Holiday Quarter, But Actually Lost Market Share|date=2019-02-20|website=iDrop News|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-30}}</ref> In April 2019, Apple reduced the price to USD $299.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/4/4/18295084/apple-homepod-price-cut-299-smart-speaker|title=Apple drops HomePod price down to $299|work=[[The Verge]]|last=Gartenberg|first=Chris|date=4 April 2019|accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{official|https://www.apple.com/homepod/}}\n* [https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2017/06/homepod-reinvents-music-in-the-home/ Apple press release]\n\n{{Apple hardware}}\n{{iOS}}\n{{Apple hardware since 1998}}\n{{Apple Inc.}}\n{{Smart speaker}}\n\n[[Category:Apple Inc. hardware]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 2017]]\n[[Category:Smart speakers]]\n", "name_user": "Penguino35", "label": "safe", "comment": "MSRP updated for HomePod, now $299 USD", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/HomePod"}
{"title_page": "Vinod Kapri", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Vinod Kapri\n| image = Vinod_Kapri.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth-date and age|15 August 1972}}\n| birth_place = [[Secunderabad]], [[India]]\n| birthname =  \n| othername =\n| spouse = [[Sakshi Joshi]]   \n| occupation  = Senior Journalist, Producer, [[Film director]], screenwriter\n}}\n\n'''Vinod Kapri''', (born 15 August 1972) is a senior Indian journalist and filmmaker. He won a National Award for the documentary film [[Can't Take This Shit Anymore]] 2014. He made his feature debut with ''[[Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho]]'' (2015) - a socio-legal satire that received extensive critical acclaim.\n\nHis second feature film Pihu has been widely appreciated in International film festivals such as Vancouver International Film Festival, Palm Springs International Film Festival (California), Fajr International Film Festival (Tehran) and Indian Film festival (Stuttgart).\n\nHis film Pihu was the Opening Film\nOf 48th International Film Festival of India (IFFI),2017. It soon became the talk of town that how a 100-minute film cast only one character that too a two-year-old girl.\n\nBefore venturing into filmmaking, he spent 23 years of his career as a journalist with media organisations like ''[[Zee News]]'', ''[[STAR News|Star News]]'' and ''[[India TV]]'', where he produced and directed various documentaries and shows including those on 13 December Parliament attack, 26/11 Mumbai attack and anti-corruption crusader Anna Hazare.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://scroll.in/article/716166/documentary-on-the-horrific-lack-of-toilets-for-rural-women-gets-national-award|title= Documentary on the horrific lack of toilets for rural women gets National Award |publisher=Scroll.in |date=25 March 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nVinod Kapri originally hails from ''[[Pithoragarh]]'' in ''[[Uttarakhand]]'' but he was born in ''[[Secunderabad]]'' in ''[[Andhra Pradesh]]''. His father was in Army,  who was posted at different places across the country. Vinod Kapri completed his early education at Kendriya Vidyalaya in states like ''[[Andhra Pradesh]]'' ''[[Secunderabad]]'', ''[[Jammu and Kashmir]]'' ''[[Udhampur]]'', ''[[West Bengal]]'' ''[[Siliguri]]'' and ''[[Uttar Pradesh]]'' ''[[Bareilly]]''.\n\nVinod was studying in class 9th, when he started writing short stories. His first story was published in 1987, when he was just 16-year-old. The story was published by Hindi daily ''[[Amar Ujala]]'', for which he received a money order of Rs.15 as a payment. Soon enough, all leading Hindi newspapers like ''[[Dainik Jagran]]'', Dainik Hindustan and Dainik Aaj would publish his articles and stories on various contemporary issues. In his school days, a novel written by him was published in a newspaper as a weekly series. Vinod graduated from ''[[Bareilly College]]'' in ''[[Uttar Pradesh]]'' and, at the age of 19, he launched his own monthly magazine Indian Econo Patrika.\n\n==Journalistic career==\n\nHis career as a journalist began with Hindi daily Jansandesh when he was only a 20-year-old. The paper was owned by famous politician Chaudhary Devi Lal and functioned amid political interference. Vinod quit the job within a few months. Same year, in 1992, he joined ''[[Dainik Jagran]]'' as a trainee. But after a span of about 4 months, he was hired as a reporter by Daily ''[[Amar Ujala]]'', soon became a subeditor. In 1995, he started his stint with ''[[Zee News]]'' as a trainee reporter. Within a year Editor ''[[Rajat Sharma]]'' assigned him an important beat to cover the United Front government. By 1996, he had established himself as a political reporter. Then he was given the responsibility of ''[[Uttar Pradesh]]'' Bureau Chief.\n\nIn 1998 he started producing and anchoring the weekly show 'Ek aur Nazariya' for Zee India TV. He also made documentaries on Dalai Lama, Homosexuals, Euthanasia, Doms of Benares, Mahakumbh of Allahabad and Aghori Sadhu of ''[[Haridwar]]''. That was the first time when Aghori Sadhus were shown on TV. \nFrom 1999 to 2001, he produced the breakfast show 'Morning Zee' for ''[[Zee News]]''. Later on channel, owner Subash Chandra decided to shift the show to main GEC channel ''[[Zee TV]]''.\n\nIn 2002, he was made an output editor of ''[[Zee News]]''. In 2004, he moved to ''[[STAR News|Star News]]'' as an Executive Producer and, over the years, rose to the post of Deputy Managing Editor. In 2007, he joined ''[[India TV]]'' as a Managing editor.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/vinod-kapris-documentary-chosen-for-indian-film-festival-stuttgart/ |title= Vinod Kapri\u2019s documentary chosen for Indian Film Festival Stuttgart |publisher= [[The Indian Express]] | accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Career Highlights==\n\nVinod conceived and executed various shows like News top 10, Hindustan Hamara, Crime Reporter, Kaun Hai, 24 Ghante 24 Reporter, Aaj Ki Pahli Khabar, Top 20 reporter, Superfast 200 and Nonstop Superfast. He also made documentaries on 13 December Parliament attack, 26/11 Mumbai terror attack and life of Anna Hazare\n\nIn 2004, he programmed a live show on a story of a Muslim couple, Arif and Gudiya. The couple became a household name for millions of viewers. The story unfolded with Arif, an Indian soldier missing for 5 years after the Kargil war, returning home to find his wife Gudiya married to another man Taufeeq and pregnant with his child. The drama that followed was broadcast live on TV for 3 full days while the entire nation was watching.\n\nVinod Kapri launched an acid attack survivor, Laxmi Saa, as an anchor for a weekly TV show 'Udaan' that was centred on social issues. He also launched a 21-year-old visually challenged youth, Kamal Prajapati, as a reporter who would host a weekly segment \u2013 Aankhen Kholo India - on social awareness that drew people's attention towards civic responsibilities.\n\n==Life after News==\nAt the end of his journalistic career, Vinod Kapri decided to take up film direction. In 2014 he won a National Award for his documentary film \u2018Can't Take This Shit Anymore\u2019. The film was based on true incidents of six women who left their husbands\u2019 homes due to lack of toilets. The incidents reported in ''[[Uttar Pradesh]]''\u2019s ''[[Kushinagar]]'' district in May 2014 caught his attention, and after a thorough reconnaissance of individual stories, he built a narrative to showcase the travesty of open defecation for Women in rural India. The film was also screened at the 12th Indian Film Festival ''[[Stuttgart]]'' in ''[[Germany]]''.\n\nHis debut film ''[[Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho]]'' was released on 26 June 2015.  Bollywood actor, ''[[Amitabh Bachchan]]'' and director ''[[Rajkumar Hirani]]'' took to ''[[Twitter]]'' to talk about Vinod Kapri\u2019s work in the film.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Miss-Tanakpur-Haazir-Ho-trailer-crosses-one-million-mark/articleshow/47441931.cms?from=mdr |title= \u2018Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho\u2019 trailer crosses one million mark|publisher=[[Times Of India]] |date=27 May 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/amitabh-bachchan-rajkumar-hirani-praise-miss-tanakpur-haazir-ho-trailer/ |title= Amitabh Bachchan, Rajukumar Hirani praise 'Miss Tanakpur Hazir Ho' trailer |publisher= The Indian Express|date=22 May 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/annu-kapoor-thanks-amitabh-bachchan-for-endorsing-miss-tanakpur-haazir-ho-770412 |title= Annu Kapoor Thanks Amitabh Bachchan for Endorsing Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho|publisher=[[NDTV]] |date=10 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesnow.tv/Entertainment/Big-B-all-prasises-for-Miss-Tanakpur-Haazir-Ho/videoshow/4476674.cms |title= Big B all praises for 'Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho'|publisher=[[The Times Of India]] |date=10 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n''[[Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho]]'', a social-political satire inspired by true incident in ''[[Rajasthan]]'', was received critical acclaim from some quarters. The film earned rave reviews from the likes of ''[[Raju Hirani]]'' and National Award-winning director ''[[Madhur Bhandarkar]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Rajkumar-Hirani-gives-positive-feedback-on-Miss-Tanakpur-Haazir-Ho/articleshow/47831227.cms |title= Rajkumar Hirani gives positive feedback on 'Miss 'Tanakpur Haazir Ho'|publisher=[[The Times Of India]] |date=27 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nVinod\u2019s sharp observations of people and dialect were well noticed; film critics discovered that his craft of satire writing has striking similarities with humour of notable writers like Sri Lal Shukla, ''[[Manohar Shyam Joshi]]'', ''[[Kashinath Singh]]'' and ''[[K P Saxena]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/miss-tanakpur-haazir-ho-making-sense-of-the-bizarre/article7358155.ece |title= Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho: Making sense of the bizarre|publisher=[[The Hindu]] |date=26 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe film starred actors such as ''[[Annu Kapoor]]'', ''[[Om Puri]]'' and ''[[Sanjay Mishra (actor)|Sanjay Mishra]]''. It also featured actors like ''[[Ravi Kishen]]'', Rahul Bagga and ''[[Hrishitaa Bhatt]]''. The story of the movie is based in ''[[Tanakpur]]'', a village in ''[[Haryana]]'', ruled by a power wielding \u2018pradhan\u2019 whose wife falls in love with a youth in the village. Discovering the reality, and spotting both his wife and the youth together, the village headman plots a conspiracy and falsely implicates the youth on charges of raping his buffalo. The 'pradhan' exploits all the resources in the system to extract his personal revenge \u2013 helped by corrupt cops while legal system seemed helpless. However, truth prevails in the end and the youth is acquitted of absurd charges. ''[[Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho]]'' uncovers the duplicity of society that allows powerful men to misuse the establishments to settle their own score.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1150627/jsp/t2/story_27992.jsp#.VdsFSPmqqkq |title= Bull in an indian village - Bullseye? Not really. But this satire is still worth a watch|publisher=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]] |date=27 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.amarujala.com/feature/multiplex/movie-review/film-review-miss-tanakpur-hazir-ho-hindi-news-jn/ |title= '\u092e\u093f\u0938 \u091f\u0928\u0915\u092a\u0941\u0930 \u0939\u093e\u091c\u093f\u0930 \u0939\u094b' \u0938\u092e\u0940\u0915\u094d\u0937\u093e\u0903 \u091a\u0915\u093f\u0924 \u0915\u0930\u0924\u0940 \u0939\u0948 \u092f\u0947 \u092b\u093f\u0932\u094d\u092e|publisher= Amarujala |date=26 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.livehindustan.com/news/entertainment/article1-film-review-movie-review-film-miss-tanakpur-hazir-ho-vinod-kapdi-om-puri-sanjay-mishra-ravi-kishan-anu-kapoor-484642.html |title= '\u092e\u093f\u0938 \u091f\u0928\u0915\u092a\u0941\u0930 \u0939\u093e\u091c\u093f\u0930 \u0939\u094b\u0902' \u0939\u093e\u0938\u094d\u092f, \u091c\u094b \u0915\u0930\u0947\u0917\u093e \u0939\u0948\u0930\u093e\u0928|publisher= Live Hindustan |date=27 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n''[[Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho]]'' was distributed by ''[[Fox Star Studios]]'' and television network ''[[Fox Networks Group Asia Pacific|STAR TV]]'' acquired its post release satellite rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/between-crass-and-class/article7364008.ece |title= Between crass and class|publisher=[[The Hindu]] |date=28 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nVinod Kapri has now launched his second film ''[[Pihu (film)|Pihu]]''. This film has a single protagonist Pihu, who is a two-year-old girl. This film is based on a true incident reported in a national daily in 2014, where a 4-year-old girl was left alone at home by the parents. The film is a [[social thriller]] by genre.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/home-alone-filmmaker-vinod-kapri-talks-about-his-next-film/|title= Home Alone Filmmaker Vinod Kapri talks about his next film| publisher=[[The Indian Express]] |date=15 May 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=40em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kapri, Vinod}}\n[[Category:Journalists from Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:People from Pithoragarh]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Kendriya Vidyalaya alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2013}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Vinod Kapri\n| image = Vinod_Kapri.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth-date and age|15 August 1972}}\n| birth_place = [[Secunderabad]], [[India]]\n| birthname =  \n| othername =\n| spouse = [[Sakshi Joshi]]   \n| occupation  = Senior Journalist, Producer, [[Film director]], screenwriter\n}}\n\n'''Vinod Kapri''', (born 15 August 1972) is a senior Indian journalist and filmmaker. He won a National Award for the documentary film [[Can't Take This Shit Anymore]] 2014. He made his feature debut with ''[[Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho]]'' (2015) - a socio-legal satire that received extensive critical acclaim.\n\nHis second feature film Pihu has been widely appreciated in International film festivals such as Vancouver International Film Festival, Palm Springs International Film Festival (California), Fajr International Film Festival (Tehran) and Indian Film festival (Stuttgart).\n\nHis film Pihu was the Opening Film\nOf 48th International Film Festival of India (IFFI),2017. It soon became the talk of town that how a 100-minute film cast only one character that too a two-year-old girl.\n\nBefore venturing into filmmaking, he spent 23 years of his career as a journalist with media organisations like ''[[Zee News]]'', ''[[STAR News|Star News]]'' and ''[[India TV]]'', where he produced and directed various documentaries and shows including those on 13 December Parliament attack, 26/11 Mumbai attack and anti-corruption crusader Anna Hazare.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://scroll.in/article/716166/documentary-on-the-horrific-lack-of-toilets-for-rural-women-gets-national-award|title= Documentary on the horrific lack of toilets for rural women gets National Award |publisher=Scroll.in |date=25 March 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nVinod Kapri originally hails from ''[[Pithoragarh]]'' in ''[[Uttarakhand]]'' but he was born in ''[[Secunderabad]]'' in ''[[Andhra Pradesh]]''. His father was in Army,  who was posted at different places across the country. Vinod Kapri completed his early education at Kendriya Vidyalaya in states like ''[[Andhra Pradesh]]'' ''[[Secunderabad]]'', ''[[Jammu and Kashmir]]'' ''[[Udhampur]]'', ''[[West Bengal]]'' ''[[Siliguri]]'' and ''[[Uttar Pradesh]]'' ''[[Bareilly]]''.\n\nVinod was studying in class 9th, when he started writing short stories. His first story was published in 1987, when he was just 16-year-old. The story was published by Hindi daily ''[[Amar Ujala]]'', for which he received a money order of Rs.15 as a payment. Soon enough, all leading Hindi newspapers like ''[[Dainik Jagran]]'', Dainik Hindustan and Dainik Aaj would publish his articles and stories on various contemporary issues. In his school days, a novel written by him was published in a newspaper as a weekly series. Vinod graduated from ''[[Bareilly College]]'' in ''[[Uttar Pradesh]]'' and, at the age of 19, he launched his own monthly magazine Indian Econo Patrika.\n\n<br />\n\n==Journalistic career==\n\nHis career as a journalist began with Hindi daily Jansandesh when he was only a 20-year-old. The paper was owned by famous politician Chaudhary Devi Lal and functioned amid political interference. Vinod quit the job within a few months. Same year, in 1992, he joined ''[[Dainik Jagran]]'' as a trainee. But after a span of about 4 months, he was hired as a reporter by Daily ''[[Amar Ujala]]'', soon became a subeditor. In 1995, he started his stint with ''[[Zee News]]'' as a trainee reporter. Within a year Editor ''[[Rajat Sharma]]'' assigned him an important beat to cover the United Front government. By 1996, he had established himself as a political reporter. Then he was given the responsibility of ''[[Uttar Pradesh]]'' Bureau Chief.\n\nIn 1998 he started producing and anchoring the weekly show 'Ek aur Nazariya' for Zee India TV. He also made documentaries on Dalai Lama, Homosexuals, Euthanasia, Doms of Benares, Mahakumbh of Allahabad and Aghori Sadhu of ''[[Haridwar]]''. That was the first time when Aghori Sadhus were shown on TV. \nFrom 1999 to 2001, he produced the breakfast show 'Morning Zee' for ''[[Zee News]]''. Later on channel, owner Subash Chandra decided to shift the show to main GEC channel ''[[Zee TV]]''.\n\nIn 2002, he was made an output editor of ''[[Zee News]]''. In 2004, he moved to ''[[STAR News|Star News]]'' as an Executive Producer and, over the years, rose to the post of Deputy Managing Editor. In 2007, he joined ''[[India TV]]'' as a Managing editor.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/vinod-kapris-documentary-chosen-for-indian-film-festival-stuttgart/ |title= Vinod Kapri\u2019s documentary chosen for Indian Film Festival Stuttgart |publisher= [[The Indian Express]] | accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Career Highlights==\n\nVinod conceived and executed various shows like News top 10, Hindustan Hamara, Crime Reporter, Kaun Hai, 24 Ghante 24 Reporter, Aaj Ki Pahli Khabar, Top 20 reporter, Superfast 200 and Nonstop Superfast. He also made documentaries on 13 December Parliament attack, 26/11 Mumbai terror attack and life of Anna Hazare\n\nIn 2004, he programmed a live show on a story of a Muslim couple, Arif and Gudiya. The couple became a household name for millions of viewers. The story unfolded with Arif, an Indian soldier missing for 5 years after the Kargil war, returning home to find his wife Gudiya married to another man Taufeeq and pregnant with his child. The drama that followed was broadcast live on TV for 3 full days while the entire nation was watching.\n\nVinod Kapri launched an acid attack survivor, Laxmi Saa, as an anchor for a weekly TV show 'Udaan' that was centred on social issues. He also launched a 21-year-old visually challenged youth, Kamal Prajapati, as a reporter who would host a weekly segment \u2013 Aankhen Kholo India - on social awareness that drew people's attention towards civic responsibilities.\n\n==Life after News==\nAt the end of his journalistic career, Vinod Kapri decided to take up film direction. In 2014 he won a National Award for his documentary film \u2018Can't Take This Shit Anymore\u2019. The film was based on true incidents of six women who left their husbands\u2019 homes due to lack of toilets. The incidents reported in ''[[Uttar Pradesh]]''\u2019s ''[[Kushinagar]]'' district in May 2014 caught his attention, and after a thorough reconnaissance of individual stories, he built a narrative to showcase the travesty of open defecation for Women in rural India. The film was also screened at the 12th Indian Film Festival ''[[Stuttgart]]'' in ''[[Germany]]''.\n\nHis debut film ''[[Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho]]'' was released on 26 June 2015.  Bollywood actor, ''[[Amitabh Bachchan]]'' and director ''[[Rajkumar Hirani]]'' took to ''[[Twitter]]'' to talk about Vinod Kapri\u2019s work in the film.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Miss-Tanakpur-Haazir-Ho-trailer-crosses-one-million-mark/articleshow/47441931.cms?from=mdr |title= \u2018Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho\u2019 trailer crosses one million mark|publisher=[[Times Of India]] |date=27 May 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/amitabh-bachchan-rajkumar-hirani-praise-miss-tanakpur-haazir-ho-trailer/ |title= Amitabh Bachchan, Rajukumar Hirani praise 'Miss Tanakpur Hazir Ho' trailer |publisher= The Indian Express|date=22 May 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/bollywood/annu-kapoor-thanks-amitabh-bachchan-for-endorsing-miss-tanakpur-haazir-ho-770412 |title= Annu Kapoor Thanks Amitabh Bachchan for Endorsing Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho|publisher=[[NDTV]] |date=10 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timesnow.tv/Entertainment/Big-B-all-prasises-for-Miss-Tanakpur-Haazir-Ho/videoshow/4476674.cms |title= Big B all praises for 'Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho'|publisher=[[The Times Of India]] |date=10 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n''[[Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho]]'', a social-political satire inspired by true incident in ''[[Rajasthan]]'', was received critical acclaim from some quarters. The film earned rave reviews from the likes of ''[[Raju Hirani]]'' and National Award-winning director ''[[Madhur Bhandarkar]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Rajkumar-Hirani-gives-positive-feedback-on-Miss-Tanakpur-Haazir-Ho/articleshow/47831227.cms |title= Rajkumar Hirani gives positive feedback on 'Miss 'Tanakpur Haazir Ho'|publisher=[[The Times Of India]] |date=27 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nVinod\u2019s sharp observations of people and dialect were well noticed; film critics discovered that his craft of satire writing has striking similarities with humour of notable writers like Sri Lal Shukla, ''[[Manohar Shyam Joshi]]'', ''[[Kashinath Singh]]'' and ''[[K P Saxena]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/cinema/cinema-reviews/miss-tanakpur-haazir-ho-making-sense-of-the-bizarre/article7358155.ece |title= Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho: Making sense of the bizarre|publisher=[[The Hindu]] |date=26 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe film starred actors such as ''[[Annu Kapoor]]'', ''[[Om Puri]]'' and ''[[Sanjay Mishra (actor)|Sanjay Mishra]]''. It also featured actors like ''[[Ravi Kishen]]'', Rahul Bagga and ''[[Hrishitaa Bhatt]]''. The story of the movie is based in ''[[Tanakpur]]'', a village in ''[[Haryana]]'', ruled by a power wielding \u2018pradhan\u2019 whose wife falls in love with a youth in the village. Discovering the reality, and spotting both his wife and the youth together, the village headman plots a conspiracy and falsely implicates the youth on charges of raping his buffalo. The 'pradhan' exploits all the resources in the system to extract his personal revenge \u2013 helped by corrupt cops while legal system seemed helpless. However, truth prevails in the end and the youth is acquitted of absurd charges. ''[[Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho]]'' uncovers the duplicity of society that allows powerful men to misuse the establishments to settle their own score.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1150627/jsp/t2/story_27992.jsp#.VdsFSPmqqkq |title= Bull in an indian village - Bullseye? Not really. But this satire is still worth a watch|publisher=[[The Telegraph (Calcutta)|The Telegraph]] |date=27 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.amarujala.com/feature/multiplex/movie-review/film-review-miss-tanakpur-hazir-ho-hindi-news-jn/ |title= '\u092e\u093f\u0938 \u091f\u0928\u0915\u092a\u0941\u0930 \u0939\u093e\u091c\u093f\u0930 \u0939\u094b' \u0938\u092e\u0940\u0915\u094d\u0937\u093e\u0903 \u091a\u0915\u093f\u0924 \u0915\u0930\u0924\u0940 \u0939\u0948 \u092f\u0947 \u092b\u093f\u0932\u094d\u092e|publisher= Amarujala |date=26 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.livehindustan.com/news/entertainment/article1-film-review-movie-review-film-miss-tanakpur-hazir-ho-vinod-kapdi-om-puri-sanjay-mishra-ravi-kishan-anu-kapoor-484642.html |title= '\u092e\u093f\u0938 \u091f\u0928\u0915\u092a\u0941\u0930 \u0939\u093e\u091c\u093f\u0930 \u0939\u094b\u0902' \u0939\u093e\u0938\u094d\u092f, \u091c\u094b \u0915\u0930\u0947\u0917\u093e \u0939\u0948\u0930\u093e\u0928|publisher= Live Hindustan |date=27 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n''[[Miss Tanakpur Haazir Ho]]'' was distributed by ''[[Fox Star Studios]]'' and television network ''[[Fox Networks Group Asia Pacific|STAR TV]]'' acquired its post release satellite rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/between-crass-and-class/article7364008.ece |title= Between crass and class|publisher=[[The Hindu]] |date=28 June 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nVinod Kapri has now launched his second film ''[[Pihu (film)|Pihu]]''. This film has a single protagonist Pihu, who is a two-year-old girl. This film is based on a true incident reported in a national daily in 2014, where a 4-year-old girl was left alone at home by the parents. The film is a [[social thriller]] by genre.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/home-alone-filmmaker-vinod-kapri-talks-about-his-next-film/|title= Home Alone Filmmaker Vinod Kapri talks about his next film| publisher=[[The Indian Express]] |date=15 May 2015 |accessdate= 24 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=40em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kapri, Vinod}}\n[[Category:Journalists from Uttarakhand]]\n[[Category:People from Pithoragarh]]\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Kendriya Vidyalaya alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian male journalists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", 